{"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A material that defines a simple sky for a "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Sky"},{"type":"text","text":" resource."}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot"]]},"schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"patch":0,"major":0},"primaryContentSections":[{"declarations":[{"platforms":["macOS"],"tokens":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"identifier","text":"ProceduralSkyMaterial"}],"languages":["swift"]}],"kind":"declarations"},{"content":[{"level":2,"text":"Overview","type":"heading","anchor":"overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial","isActive":true},{"text":" provides a way to create an effective background quickly by defining procedural parameters for the sun, the sky and the ground. The sky and ground are defined by a main color, a color at the horizon, and an easing curve to interpolate between them. Suns are described by a position in the sky, a color, and a max angle from the sun at which the easing curve ends. The max angle therefore defines the size of the sun in the sky.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial"},{"text":" supports up to 4 suns, using the color, and energy, direction, and angular distance of the first four ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/DirectionalLight3D","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" nodes in the scene. This means that the suns are defined individually by the properties of their corresponding "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/DirectionalLight3D"},{"type":"text","text":"s and globally by "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/sunAngleMax"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/sunCurve","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" uses a lightweight shader to draw the sky and is therefore suited for real time updates. This makes it a great option for a sky that is simple and computationally cheap, but unrealistic. If you need a more realistic procedural option, use "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PhysicalSkyMaterial"},{"text":".","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"kind":"content"}],"sections":[],"topicSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/groundBottomColor","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/groundCurve","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/groundEnergyMultiplier","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/groundHorizonColor","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/skyCover","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/skyCoverModulate","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/skyCurve","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/skyEnergyMultiplier","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/skyHorizonColor","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/skyTopColor","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/sunAngleMax","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/sunCurve","doc:\/\/SwiftGo